{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18341"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18341"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74676"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11059"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60159"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25844"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74676"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with difficulty in extending her toes and dorsiflexing her foot after a recent ankle sprain. She is a recreational runner and has no significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild swelling around the ankle, but no significant tenderness. Muscle strength testing reveals weakness in toe extension and foot dorsiflexion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Soleus","Peroneus longus","Tibialis anterior","Gastrocnemius","Extensor digitorum longus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms of difficulty in extending the toes and dorsiflexing the foot suggest an issue with the \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor digitorum longus\u003C/strong\u003E. This muscle is located in the anterior compartment of the leg and is primarily responsible for extending the toes and assisting in dorsiflexion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibialis anterior\u003C/strong\u003E is also involved in dorsiflexion of the foot, but it does not extend the toes. Weakness in toe extension specifically points towards the extensor digitorum longus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrocnemius\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esoleus\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are located in the posterior compartment of the leg and are responsible for plantarflexion, not dorsiflexion or toe extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eperoneus longus\u003C/strong\u003E is located in the lateral compartment of the leg and is involved in eversion and plantarflexion of the foot, not dorsiflexion or toe extension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The extensor digitorum longus is responsible for extending the toes and dorsiflexing the foot.","Understanding the function and location of lower limb muscles is crucial for diagnosing and managing musculoskeletal injuries.","The extensor digitorum longus is located in the anterior compartment of the leg."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60159"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18341"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60159"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T15:27:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T15:28:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11059"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74676"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,